Text zones.

A text zone names a region of the map. When the player walks into it, the zone's name is spoken; when they walk back out, the game announces that they're leaving it. Text zones are how you label the places in a map — kitchen, courtyard, east hallway, the docks — so the player always knows where they are by ear as they move around. They're one of the most useful entities for making a large map legible: liberal use of text zones turns a featureless grid into a set of named rooms and areas.

How a text zone works.

The zone covers a rectangular area. Crossing into it speaks its name; crossing out of it announces that the player is leaving. The player only hears the name once on entry, not repeatedly while standing inside, and only hears the leaving announcement once on the way out. Where text zones overlap, the most recently placed one covering the player's tile is the one that's announced, so a smaller zone laid inside a larger one names the spot where they overlap.

Text zones double as named destinations. The go-to-zone feature and the zones menu let the player jump between text zones by name, so every text zone you place is also a waypoint the player can travel to — another reason to name the important spots in a map.

Text zone fields.

The text zone form takes the following:

Coordinates. A minimum and maximum x and y (and a minimum and maximum z on 3d maps), marking the named area.

Text. The name spoken when the player enters, and echoed when they leave.

Authoring text zones by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a text zone is: text_zone minx maxx miny maxy "text". On 3d maps a minimum and maximum z follow the y pair: text_zone minx maxx miny maxy minz maxz "text". The text is wrapped in double quotes so the name may contain spaces.
